[30;1m1218 | [0m[35m  ``Str`` and ``CStr``. ``Unicode`` and ``CUnicode`` are considered deprecated.[0m
[30;1m1219 | [0m[35m  For now, no deprecation warning is issued on use of these deprecated trait[0m
[30;1m1220 | [0m[35m  types, but in Traits 6.1.0 and later, warnings may be issued, and in Traits[0m
[30;1m1221 | [0m[35m  7.0.0 these trait types may be removed. It's recommended that users update[0m
[30;1m1222 | [0m[35m  all uses of ``Unicode`` to ``Str`` and ``CUnicode`` to ``CStr`` to avoid[0m
[30;1m1223 | [0m[35m  warnings or errors in the future.[0m

[30;1m940 | [0m[35m* When listening for changes to the items of a :class:`.List` trait, an index[0m
[30;1m941 | [0m[35m  or slice set operation no longer performs an equality check between the[0m
[30;1m942 | [0m[35m  replaced elements and the replacement elements when deciding whether to issue[0m
[30;1m943 | [0m[35m  a notification; instead, a notification is always issued if at least one[0m
[30;1m944 | [0m[35m  element was replaced. For example, consider the following class::[0m
[30;1m945 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m946 | [0m[35m    class Selection(HasTraits):[0m

[30;1m1254 | [0m[35m  If you have code that imports directly from Traits modules and subpackages[0m
[30;1m1255 | [0m[35m  instead of from ``traits.api`` or the other subpackage ``api`` modules, some[0m

[30;1m215 | [0m[35m.. note::[0m
[30;1m216 | [0m[35m    The patterns ``"+"`` and ``"-"`` both match all traits on a ``HasTraits``[0m
[30;1m217 | [0m[35m    object. The two patterns behave almost identically, but[0m
[30;1m218 | [0m[35m    there's a difference at the implementation level. The ``"+"`` pattern[0m
[30;1m219 | [0m[35m    registers one trait-level notifier for each trait on the target object,[0m
[30;1m220 | [0m[35m    while the ``"-"`` pattern registers a single *object*-level notifier on the[0m
[30;1m221 | [0m[35m    target object. As a result, the two patterns may have different[0m

[30;1m641 | [0m[35mUnion[0m
[30;1m642 | [0m[35m:::::[0m
[30;1m643 | [0m[35mThe Union trait accepts a value that is considered valid by at least one[0m
[30;1m644 | [0m[35mof the traits in its definition. It is a simpler and therefore less error-prone[0m
[30;1m645 | [0m[35malternative to the `Either` trait, which allows more complex constructs and[0m
[30;1m646 | [0m[35mmay sometimes exhibit mysterious validation behaviour. The Union trait however,[0m

[30;1m71 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m72 | [0m[35mThis works, but it has a downside that the histogram is re-computed every[0m
[30;1m73 | [0m[35mtime the property is accessed.  For small images, this is probably OK, but[0m
[30;1m74 | [0m[35mfor larger images, or if you are working with many images at once, this may[0m
[30;1m75 | [0m[35mimpact performance.  In these cases, you can specify that the property[0m
[30;1m76 | [0m[35mshould **cache** the returned value and use that value until the trait(s)[0m
[30;1m77 | [0m[35mthe property depend on changes::[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m445[0m[34m of [0m[33m918[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000600[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Windows[0m

[30;1m69 | [0m[35m            )[0m
[30;1m70 | [0m[35m            return hist[0m
[30;1m71 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m72 | [0m[35mThis works, but it has a downside that the histogram is re-computed every[0m
[30;1m73 | [0m[35mtime the property is accessed.  For small images, this is probably OK, but[0m
[30;1m74 | [0m[35mfor larger images, or if you are working with many images at once, this may[0m
[30;1m75 | [0m[35mimpact performance.  In these cases, you can specify that the property[0m
[30;1m76 | [0m[35mshould **cache** the returned value and use that value until the trait(s)[0m

[30;1m127 | [0m[35mpost-initialization setup of state: you can define a ``traits_init`` method[0m

[30;1m129 | [0m[35minitialization process.  When it has been called, all initial values will[0m

[30;1m93 | [0m[35m    date_acquired = Date(datetime.date(2020, 1, 1))[0m
[30;1m94 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m95 | [0m[35mBut it would be better if we could set it to a dynamic value.  For example,[0m
[30;1m96 | [0m[35ma reasonable default would be today's date.  You can provide this sort of[0m
[30;1m97 | [0m[35mdynamically declared default by using a specially-named method which has[0m
[30;1m98 | [0m[35mthe pattern ``_<trait-name>_default`` and which returns the default value.[0m
[30;1m99 | [0m[35mSo we could write::[0m

[30;1m24 | [0m[35mIn some cases however, the cost of computing the current value of a property[0m
[30;1m25 | [0m[35mmay be fairly expensive, so it is often a good idea to *cache* the most[0m
[30;1m26 | [0m[35mrecently computed value of the property, and return it as the value of the[0m
[30;1m27 | [0m[35mproperty until one of the traits the property depends upon changes value, at[0m
[30;1m28 | [0m[35mwhich point the cache should be cleared and the property value recomputed the[0m
[30;1m29 | [0m[35mnext time its value is requested.[0m

[30;1m64 | [0m[35m* |@observe| decorator supports setting up change handlers prior to setting[0m
[30;1m65 | [0m[35m  object state at instantiation.[0m
[30;1m66 | [0m[35m* |@observe| decorator sets up change handlers for all instances of a class[0m
[30;1m67 | [0m[35m  and those change handlers can be inherited by subclasses.[0m
[30;1m68 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m580 | [0m[35mAdaptation enables a programming style in which each component or service in an[0m
[30;1m581 | [0m[35mapplication defines an interface through which it would like to receive[0m
[30;1m582 | [0m[35minformation. Objects that need to communicate with the component declare[0m
[30;1m583 | [0m[35man adapter for that interface, as illustrated in the figure below.[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m680[0m[34m of [0m[33m918[0m[31m ]--[0m
   Rule Id: [34mBD000610[0m
       Tag: [34mSecurity.Backdoor.LOLBAS.Linux[0m
  Severity: [36mModerate[0m, Confidence: [36mLow[0m
  Filename: [33m/traits-7.0.2/docs/source/traits_user_manual/advanced.rst[0m

[30;1m46 | [0m[35minitialization. For performance purposes, a default initializer method is[0m
[30;1m47 | [0m[35mcalled when:[0m
[30;1m48 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m49 | [0m[35m1. the attribute value is accessed the first time or[0m
[30;1m50 | [0m[35m2. an instance is constructed with a specific value, if there is a change[0m
[30;1m51 | [0m[35m   handler defined for the trait. This is needed so the default can be reported[0m
[30;1m52 | [0m[35m   as the old value (see :ref:`static-notification`).[0m

[30;1m70 | [0m[35m============================[0m
[30;1m71 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m72 | [0m[35mOccasionally it is necessary to find the chain of event dispatches in traits[0m
[30;1m73 | [0m[35mclasses. To help with debugging, a |record_events| context manager is provided[0m
[30;1m74 | [0m[35min :mod:`traits.util.event_tracer`. Trait change events taking place inside the[0m
[30;1m75 | [0m[35mcontext block will be recorded in a change event container (see example below)[0m

[30;1m52 | [0m[35m    -------[0m

[31m--[ [0m[34mMatch #[0m[33m774[0m[34m of [0m[33m918[0m[31m ]--[0m

[30;1m35 | [0m[35m    """[0m
[30;1m36 | [0m[35m    node = nodes[-1][0m
[30;1m37 | [0m[35m    graph = ObserverGraph(node=node)[0m
[30;1m38 | [0m[35m    for node in nodes[:-1][::-1]:[0m

[30;1m25 | [0m[35m    a trait on an HasTraits instance, for observing items in a list, etc.[0m
[30;1m26 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m27 | [0m[35m    Given an ``ObserverGraph``, observers are visited from the root node[0m
[30;1m28 | [0m[35m    to the leaf nodes. The first observer (root node) will be given the object[0m
[30;1m29 | [0m[35m    the user wants to observe. It knows how to obtain observable(s) for[0m
[30;1m30 | [0m[35m    attaching notifiers. It also knows what objects should be given to the[0m
[30;1m31 | [0m[35m    downstream/children observers in the same graph.[0m

[30;1m21 | [0m[35mvalidation of the delegate attribute are used for the deferring attribute;[0m
[30;1m22 | [0m[35mchanges to either one are reflected in both. In prototyping, the deferring[0m
[30;1m23 | [0m[35mattribute gets its value and validation from the prototype attribute, *until the[0m
[30;1m24 | [0m[35mdeferring attribute is explicitly changed*. At that point, while the deferring[0m
[30;1m25 | [0m[35mattribute still uses the prototype's validation, the link between the values is[0m
[30;1m26 | [0m[35mbroken, and the two attributes can change independently. This is essentially a[0m
[30;1m27 | [0m[35m"copy on write" scheme.[0m

[30;1m8 | [0m[35mOne of the advanced capabilities of the Traits package is its support for trait[0m
[30;1m9 | [0m[35mattributes to defer their definition and value to another object than the one[0m
[30;1m10 | [0m[35mthe attribute is defined on. This has many applications, especially in cases[0m
[30;1m11 | [0m[35mwhere objects are logically contained within other objects and may wish to[0m
[30;1m12 | [0m[35minherit or derive some attributes from the object they are contained in or[0m
[30;1m13 | [0m[35massociated with. Deferring leverages the common "has-a" relationship between[0m
[30;1m14 | [0m[35mobjects, rather than the "is-a" relationship that class inheritance provides.[0m
